Part 3

The boy arrived at three in the afternoon, when the shadows of the neem trees had stretched fully across the stones of the courtyard well. 

He was carrying a cheap blue canvas bag with a rusted zip that didn't go all the way to the end, showing a corner of a grey towel inside. His shoes were cheap black canvas, the rubber soles worn thin, with a line of grey station dust outlining the seams near his toes.

He stood near the swollen wooden entrance door. He didn't knock; he simply stood there, his hands holding the faded canvas straps of the bag, looking up at the marble nameplate *Sen family* with the quiet concentration of a passenger checking a train ticket.

Vikram heard a voice from the register table — Ananya, asking something — and then the boy's reply, soft, an Odia accent in it. He came out of the back room carrying a heavy plastic bucket of white lime wash.

He set the bucket down on the stone verandah. 

The boy looked at Vikram's face, his eyes moving slowly from the white splash on the temple to the faded cotton shirt, and then down to his calloused hands. Then he bowed slightly, his hands folding near his chest in a respectful gesture.

"Vikram uncle?"

"Yes," Vikram said, wiping his brow with his arm.

"I am Rehman," the boy said.

Vikram looked at the boy's eyes. They were large, dark, and the shape of the eyelids was identical to the ones that had watched him in the Salt Lake newspaper office ten years ago. 

But they had none of her nervous restlessness; they were still and calm.

"Your train was on time?" Vikram asked.

"Two hours late at Howrah," the boy said, shifting his bag. "I took the local bus to the Bagbazar crossing, and the conductor showed me the lane."

Sarita came out of the hallway, leaning on her bamboo cane. She looked at the boy and his small canvas bag. Vikram remembered her saying something about the dal, something about Ramesh's old bed in the side hall. The boy had nodded. Later, Sarita told him she had taken one look at the boy's shoes — the rubber soles worn down to almost nothing — and decided the rest immediately.

---

He washed at the municipal tap. He drew the water with one hand, his canvas bag kept carefully on the stone ledge near Ananya's table.

Vikram watched him from the verandah steps. The boy's neck was thin, the vertebrae standing out under the collar of his faded blue shirt as he bent over the iron pipe. 

He washed his face twice, using a small piece of red soap he had brought in his bag. It was the cheap, local brand of soap sold at the small station shops in Cuttack. 

He wiped his face with a small green hand towel, then walked back to the steps. "Where is the work, uncle?" he asked.

"The work is everywhere," Vikram said. "Today, we are whitewashing the kitchen wall. Tomorrow, the medicine delivery arrives from the college hospital."

"I can do the whitewashing," the boy said.

He picked up the spare brush leaning near the bucket. He didn't ask how to hold it, and he didn't ask where he should start. 

He simply went to the kitchen door, looked at the grey patch on the wall where the plaster had been repaired, and began to paint.

His strokes were slow, slightly uneven at first, but he didn't stop until the grey brick was covered in clean, flat white. 

Vikram stood beside him, taking the second brush from the bucket. For one hour, they painted the kitchen wall together in silence, the smell of fresh lime and damp brick rising between them in the small room.

---

Outside, the afternoon light faded slowly. The shadow of the neem trees covered the well. 

Ananya sat at her table, her pen moving regularly as she entered the evening medicines in the green cloth ledger.

At five, Ramu's nephew brought the steel kettle. It was red tea. 

Shankar's jaggery was gone, but Sarita had bought a small cone of palm sugar from the market. They sat on the verandah steps, three mismatched glasses between them.

"It is good tea," Rehman said, blowing on the hot glass.

"It is cheap," Sarita said, sitting near Ananya's table. "But it keeps us warm."

The boy drank. He looked at the neem trees, at the old marble nameplate, and then at the white kitchen wall he had painted.

Ananya kept her eyes on the green cloth ledger. Her pen continued moving at the same pace it had before the tea arrived.

Vikram noticed this, but it didn't register as odd at the time.

"My mother told me," Rehman said, his voice quiet. "She said you were a tycoon once."

Vikram looked down at his glass. The red tea was hot, the palm sugar sweet and dark.

"She was mistaken," Vikram said. "I was never a tycoon."

The boy smiled. It was a small, quiet smile that had nothing of the boardroom in it, and nothing of the city.

"I know," Rehman said. "The tycoon would never have painted the kitchen."

Vikram drank his tea. The Bagbazar tap water was heavy, but the red tea tasted of the fresh lime on his brush and the neem leaves in the wind. 

He looked at the yellow envelope sitting on the study table inside. The envelope was closed, the boy was here, and as the night settled over the Sen family house, the red tea in his hand was enough.

[End of Part 3]
